.TH strchr 3 (date) "Linux man-pages (unreleased)"
.SH NAME
strchr, strrchr \- locate character in string
.SH LIBRARY
Standard C library
.RI ( libc ,\~ \-lc )
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include <string.h>
.P
.BI "char *strchr(const char *" s ", int " c );
.BI "char *strrchr(const char *" s ", int " c );
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.TP
.BR strchr ()
The
.BR strchr ()
function returns a pointer to the first occurrence
of the character
.I c
in the string
.IR s .
.IP
It is equivalent to both of the following expressions:
.IP
.in +4n
.EX
memchr(s, c, strlen(s) + 1)
strpbrk(s, (char [2]){c, \[aq]\[rs]0\[aq]})
.EE
.in
.TP
.BR strrchr ()
The
.BR strrchr ()
function returns a pointer to the last occurrence
of the character
.I c
in the string
.IR s .
.IP
It is equivalent to
.IP
.in +4n
.EX
memrchr(s, c, strlen(s) + 1)
.EE
.in
.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.BR strchr ()
and
.BR strrchr ()
functions return a pointer to
the matched character or NULL if the character is not found.
The terminating null byte is considered part of the string,
so that if
.I c
is specified as \[aq]\[rs]0\[aq],
these functions return a pointer to the terminator.
.SH ATTRIBUTES
For an explanation of the terms used in this section, see
.BR attributes (7).
